## Error Handling

### ❌ Mistake #1: Not Handling Async Errors

```javascript
// WRONG - unhandled promise rejection
router.get('/users', async (req, res) => {
  const users = await User.find();  // If this throws, app crashes
  res.json(users);
});
```

**Problem**: Unhandled promise rejections crash the application.

✅ **Solution**: Always use try-catch with next()

```javascript
// CORRECT
router.get('/users', async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const users = await User.find();
    res.json({ success: true, data: users });
  } catch (error) {
    next(error);
  }
});

// BETTER - Use async handler wrapper
const asyncHandler = (fn) => (req, res, next) => {
  Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);
};

router.get('/users', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  const users = await User.find();
  res.json({ success: true, data: users });
}));
```

### ❌ Mistake #2: Generic Error Messages

```javascript
// WRONG - unhelpful error
throw new Error('Error occurred');
```

✅ **Solution**: Use descriptive, custom errors

```javascript
// CORRECT
throw new ValidationError('Email format is invalid', [
  { field: 'email', message: 'Must be a valid email address' }
]);
```

### ❌ Mistake #3: Not Using Global Error Handler

```javascript
// WRONG - handling errors in each route
router.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const user = await createUser(req.body);
    res.json(user);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });  // Inconsistent format
  }
});
```

✅ **Solution**: Use global error handler middleware

```javascript
// CORRECT - in app.js
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  const statusCode = err.statusCode || 500;
  res.status(statusCode).json({
    success: false,
    error: {
      code: err.code || 'INTERNAL_ERROR',
      message: err.isOperational ? err.message : 'Something went wrong'
    }
  });
});
```

