## Async/Await Issues

### ❌ Mistake #4: Mixing Callbacks and Async/Await

```javascript
// WRONG - mixing patterns
router.get('/users', async (req, res, next) => {
  User.find((err, users) => {  // Callback style
    if (err) return next(err);
    res.json(users);
  });
});
```

✅ **Solution**: Use async/await consistently

```javascript
// CORRECT
router.get('/users', async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const users = await User.find();
    res.json({ success: true, data: users });
  } catch (error) {
    next(error);
  }
});
```

### ❌ Mistake #5: Not Awaiting Promises

```javascript
// WRONG - forgot await
const user = User.findById(id);  // Returns a promise, not user
console.log(user.name);  // undefined
```

✅ **Solution**: Always await async operations

```javascript
// CORRECT
const user = await User.findById(id);
console.log(user.name);  // Works
```

### ❌ Mistake #6: Sequential Awaits When Parallel is Possible

```javascript
// WRONG - slow, sequential execution
const user = await User.findById(userId);
const posts = await Post.find({ author: userId });
const comments = await Comment.find({ author: userId });
```

✅ **Solution**: Use Promise.all for parallel operations

```javascript
// CORRECT - fast, parallel execution
const [user, posts, comments] = await Promise.all([
  User.findById(userId),
  Post.find({ author: userId }),
  Comment.find({ author: userId })
]);
```

